window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"The branch of Biology that deals with the principles of classification of organisms is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"biological index","B":"nomenclature","C":"taxonomy","D":"ecology"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Taxonomy is the branch of biology that categorizes all living things. It was developed by the Swedish botanist Carolus Linnaeus, who lived during the 18th Century, and his system of classification is still used today. Taxonomy involves the classification of organisms into a hierarchy of taxa, including kingdom, phylum, class, order, family, genus, and species.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following structures is a tissue?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Vessel element","B":"Blood","C":"Sieve tube element","D":"Erythrocyte"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A tissue is a group of cells that work together to perform a specific function. In this case, blood is considered a tissue because it is composed of different types of cells (red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets) that work together to perform various functions such as oxygen transportation, immune response, and clotting. The other options (Vessel element, Sieve tube element, Erythrocyte) are individual cell types, not tissues.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Which of the following cells are not regarded as specialized?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Sperm cells","B":"Root tip cells","C":"Muscle cells","D":"Somatic cells"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Specialized cells are cells that have a specific role to perform in the body, they are adapted to carry out this role. Sperm cells, root tip cells, and muscle cells are all examples of specialized cells as they have specific roles in reproduction, growth, and movement respectively. However, somatic cells are not specialized because they make up the majority of the body's cells and perform the basic functions of life, they are not adapted for a specific role.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Which of the following pairs of cells carry out the same functions?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Cheek cell and red blood cell","B":"Spermatozoan and ovum","C":"Palisade cell and epidermal cell","D":"Root tips cell and guard cell"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Spermatozoan and ovum both carry out the function of reproduction. The spermatozoan (male gamete) and ovum (female gamete) fuse during fertilization to form a zygote, which develops into a new organism. Other options are incorrect because the cells listed do not carry out the same functions. For example, cheek cells are involved in protection and secretion, while red blood cells are involved in oxygen transport.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"If Amoeba is placed in a salt solution, the contractile vacuoles would","images":[],"options":{"A":"be bursting more frequently","B":"be more numerous","C":"be formed less frequently","D":"grow bigger before they burst"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a hypertonic solution (such as a salt solution), water moves out of the Amoeba's cell to balance the external salt concentration. This leads to a decrease in the internal water content of the cell.     The primary function of the contractile vacuole in Amoeba is to expel excess water that enters the cell. In a hypertonic environment, less water enters the cell, so the contractile vacuole doesn't need to expel water as frequently.    Therefore, the contractile vacuole would not be bursting more frequently; instead, it would be formed less frequently due to the decreased water intake.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"In which of the following habitats is Paramecium not found?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Pond","B":"Aquarium","C":"Lake","D":"Puddle"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Amoeba, Paramecium, Sporozoans and some other protists cannot survive in the aquarium.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The following processes are involved in water movement in the endodermis except","images":[],"options":{"A":"osmosis","B":"vacuolar pathway","C":"diffusion","D":"active transport"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The endodermis is a layer of cells in plant roots that plays a crucial role in water and nutrient uptake. The following processes are involved in water movement in the endodermis:    Osmosis: Water enters the endodermis through osmosis, driven by a concentration gradient.    Vacuolar pathway: Water can move through the vacuoles of endodermal cells, allowing for the transport of water and solutes.    Active transport: Endodermal cells can actively transport solutes and water into the plant, using energy-dependent mechanisms.    However, diffusion is not directly involved in water movement in the endodermis. Diffusion is the random movement of molecules from high to low concentration, but it's not a primary mechanism for water uptake in the endodermis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Cells that utilize a lot of energy are characterised by the presence of a large number of","images":[],"options":{"A":"vacuoles","B":"mitochondria","C":"endoplasmic reticulum","D":"ribosomes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Cells that utilize a lot of energy are characterized by the presence of a large number of mitochondria. Mitochondria are known as the powerhouses of the cell because they produce ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the cell's main energy-carrying molecule. This is why cells that require a lot of energy, such as muscle cells, have a large number of mitochondria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The diagram beside represents the phenomenon of growth in a meristematic cell of a plant        Use it to answer this question     The part labelled II in the diagram is the","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"centriole","B":"chloroplast","C":"chromatid","D":"tonoplast"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The part labelled II is one of the sister chromatids","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The diagram beside represents the phenomenon of growth in a meristematic cell of a plant        Use it to answer this question    The part labelled I is called the","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"nucleolus","B":"centromere","C":"centriole","D":"spindle"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The spindle fibre is closely attached to the centriole.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Secondary growth is brought about by the activities of the","images":[],"options":{"A":"phellogen and phelloderm","B":"phellogen and procambium","C":"vascular cambium and phelloderm","D":"vascular cambium and phellogen"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Secondary growth in plants is brought about by the activities of the vascular cambium and the cork cambium (also known as phellogen). The vascular cambium is responsible for producing new transport cells in the xylem and phloem, while the cork cambium (phellogen) produces cells that eventually become the bark of the plant. Therefore, the correct answer is 'vascular cambium and phellogen'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"A monocot root is different from a dicot root by having","images":[],"options":{"A":"endodermis","B":"cambium","C":"wide pith","D":"root hairs"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A monocot root is different from a dicot root by having a wide pith. The pith is the central part of the root or stem containing parenchyma tissue. In monocots, this pith is wide, while in dicots it is comparatively smaller. The other options like endodermis, cambium, and root hairs are common to both monocot and dicot roots.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following statements best describes haemoglobin? It is","images":[],"options":{"A":"yellowish in colour","B":"a red blood cell","C":"an oxygen carrying pigment","D":"needed for blood clotting"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Haemoglobin is an oxygen-carrying pigment. It is a protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen from the lungs to the body's tissues and returns carbon dioxide from the tissues back to the lungs. It is not yellowish in colour, it is not a red blood cell (but is found within them), and it is not needed for blood clotting (that's the role of platelets and clotting factors).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"Inhaled air is made warm and moist in the","images":[],"options":{"A":"epiglottis","B":"nasal cavity","C":"trachea","D":"mouth"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The nasal cavity is responsible for warming and moistening the air we inhale. This is because the nasal cavity is lined with a mucous membrane that secretes mucus to moisten the air and has a rich blood supply that warms the air.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following structures is not involved in respiration?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Lungs Books","B":"Mouth","C":"Stomach","D":"Trachea"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The stomach is not involved in respiration. Respiration is the process of gas exchange between the body and the environment, and it involves structures like the lungs, trachea, and mouth. The stomach, on the other hand, is involved in digestion, not respiration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Filtrate in the Bowman's capsule contains vitamins because","images":[],"options":{"A":"only a little amount is required by the body","B":"they can be reabsorbed into the blood.","C":"they have low molecular weight.","D":"most of them are fat soluble"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The filtrate in the Bowman's capsule contains vitamins because they have low molecular weight. The Bowman's capsule is a part of the nephron in the kidneys that performs the first step in the filtration of blood to form urine. It filters out small molecules such as water, glucose, amino acids, and urea, along with vitamins, which are small enough to pass through the filtration membrane. Larger molecules like proteins and blood cells are too large to pass through and remain in the blood.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"More sweat is produced during muscular exercise because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the contracting  muscles produce water","B":"fermentation occurs in muscles","C":"the temperature of the body rises","D":"the muscles fatigues"},"answer":"C","explanation":"More sweat is produced during muscular exercise because the temperature of the body rises. When we exercise, our muscles generate heat as a byproduct of energy production. This heat increases our body temperature. To cool down, our body produces sweat, which evaporates from the skin surface and helps to dissipate the heat, thereby regulating body temperature.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following neutrons may not have myelin sheath","images":[],"options":{"A":"Effector cells","B":"Intermediate neurons","C":"Motor neurons","D":"Sensory neurons"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Intermediate neurons (also known as interneurons) typically lack myelin sheaths. They are primarily involved in relaying signals between sensory and motor neurons within the central nervous system and often have short axons that do not require myelination.    Effector cells, are not neurons. Effector cells refer to muscle or gland cells that carry out the body's responses to stimuli. These cells receive signals from motor neurons but are not themselves neurons, so the concept of a myelin sheath does not apply to them. Therefore, the correct answer is Intermediate neurons, which are typically not myelinated.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following is not an effector organ?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Tongue","B":"Skin","C":"Nose bridge","D":"Ear glands"},"answer":"B","explanation":"External sense organs e.g skin are receptor hence it is not an effector organ.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"During sexual reproduction in Paramecium, how many times does the zygote divide to produce eight nuclei?","images":[],"options":{"A":"1","B":"2","C":"3","D":"4"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In Paramecium, during sexual reproduction, the zygote (fertilized cell) undergoes three rounds of cell division to produce eight nuclei. This process is called multiple fission.    This is the division sequence:    1. Zygote (1 nucleus) \u2192 2 nuclei (1st division)  2. 2 nuclei \u2192 4 nuclei (2nd division)  3. 4 nuclei \u2192 8 nuclei (3rd division)    The resulting eight nuclei will then develop into eight daughter cells, each with a complete set of chromosomes","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"The testes in male mammals descend into the scrotal sac because","images":[],"options":{"A":"there is congestion in the lower abdomen","B":"they run the risk of being destroyed","C":"they need special support","D":"they require a relatively low temperature"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The testes in male mammals descend into the scrotal sac because they require a relatively low temperature for the production of sperm. This is a process known as testicular descent. The temperature in the scrotal sac is lower than the body temperature, which is necessary for the proper development and functioning of the sperm.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Some animals return to water bodies to reproduce because","images":[],"options":{"A":"natural enemies destroy their egg on land","B":"water nourishes the embryos and their young ones","C":"they are close to their ancestors and imitate them","D":"the temperature on land is not suitable for the development of their embryos"},"answer":"D","explanation":"This is due to the fact that the absolute temperature of the land is not suitable enough for the embryo to develop.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : RELEVANCE OF BIOLOGY TO AGRICULTURE","question":"Which of the following methods is appropriate for the cultivation of cassava?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Budding","B":"Fragmentation","C":"Root cutting","D":"Stem cutting"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Cassava is propagated through stem cutting. This is a type of vegetative propagation where a section of the stem is planted in the ground and it grows into a new plant. This method is preferred because it ensures that the new plants will have the same characteristics as the parent plant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"What will be the chromosome number of the hybrid of two varieties of a plant with 36 chromosomes in the endosperm cell?","images":[],"options":{"A":"12","B":"24","C":"36","D":"48"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In plants, the endosperm cell is triploid (3n), resulting from the fusion of a sperm nucleus with the polar nuclei in the embryo sac. Since the endosperm cell has 36 chromosomes, we can set up the equation:    3n = 36    To find the haploid chromosome number (n), we divide by 3:    n = 36 \u00f7 3  n = 12    Since the hybrid is formed by the fusion of two haploid gametes (sperm and egg), the chromosome number of the hybrid will be 2n, or:    2n = 2 \u00d7 12  2n = 24    So, the chromosome number of the hybrid will be 24.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Kreb's cycle occurs in the","images":[],"options":{"A":"mitochondria","B":"cytoplasm","C":"nucleus","D":"ribosomes"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Kreb's cycle, also known as the citric acid cycle or the tricarboxylic acid cycle, occurs in the mitochondria of a cell. It is a series of chemical reactions used by all aerobic organisms to generate energy through the oxidation of acetyl-CoA derived from carbohydrates, fats, and proteins into carbon dioxide and chemical energy in the form of adenosine triphosphate (ATP).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"The process whereby electrons are emitted from chlorophyll and returned to it unchanged is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"non-cyclic phosphorylation","B":"photochemical reaction","C":"phosphorylation","D":"cyclic  phosphorylation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The process whereby electrons are emitted from chlorophyll and returned to it unchanged is known as cyclic phosphorylation. In cyclic phosphorylation, the electron travels a short circuit (it returns to the chlorophyll molecule from which it was excited), and the only product is ATP.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following statements about photosynthesis is not true?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Plants can photosynthesize without an increase in dry weight","B":"Carbon dioxide is absorbed by the leaves in bright light","C":"Oxygen is produced during photosynthesis from the breakdown of water","D":"Photosynthesis occurs in green plants"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Carbon dioxide is absorbed by the leaves in bright light:takes place in green plants during photosynthesis as if (CO2) enters the leaves through the stomata opening on the leaf surface.    Oxygen is produced during photosynthesis from the breakdown of water:takes place during the light reaction stage of photosynthesis.   Photosynthesis takes place in green plants.  Plants can photosynthesize without an increase in dry weight is not true","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The equation below represents the process of glycolysis        X in the equation represents","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Glucose diphosphate","B":"Glucose phosphate","C":"Glucose triphosphate","D":"Fructose phosphate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"X in the equation represents Glucose phosphate in glycolysis","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"The removal of all the phloem tissues of the stem of a plant close to the root system for a long period of time is likely to","images":[],"options":{"A":"provide more energy to the roots","B":"accumulate more starch in the roots","C":"cause the underground roots to develop buds","D":"cause the plant to wither and die"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Phloem is a type of tissue in vascular plants that transports nutrients, including sugars produced during photosynthesis, from the leaves (where they are produced) to other parts of the plant. If all the phloem tissues are removed, the plant will not be able to transport these nutrients, leading to nutrient deficiency and eventually causing the plant to wither and die.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Conversion of glucose to starch in the leaf during the day principally","images":[],"options":{"A":"enables photosynthesis","B":"prevents osmotic problems","C":"enables the leaf to store the starch","D":"enables glucose to be used up."},"answer":"C","explanation":"The sugar produced during photosynthesis is converted to starch till night-time.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following groups of substances are not six-carbon compounds?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Glucose and Lactose","B":"Lactose and Cellulose","C":"Glucose, Lactose and Pyruvate","D":"Pyruvate ad cellulose"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The question asks for substances that are not six-carbon compounds. Glucose and lactose are both six-carbon compounds. Pyruvate, however, is a three-carbon compound, and cellulose is a polymer made up of glucose units. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Pyruvate and cellulose'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"A purple colour was obtained when Sodium Hydroxide solution and a drop of Copper Sulphate solution were added to a food substance. The food substance is likely to be a","images":[],"options":{"A":"carbohydrate","B":"fat","C":"protein","D":"sugar"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The test described in the question is the Biuret test, which is used to detect the presence of proteins. When sodium hydroxide and copper sulphate are added to a protein, a purple color is produced. Therefore, the food substance is likely to be a protein.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following enzymes is active in the duodenum?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Pepsin","B":"Renin","C":"Trypsin","D":"Amylase"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The duodenum is the first part of the small intestine where the process of digestion continues. Trypsin is one of the enzymes that is active in the duodenum. It is produced in the pancreas and released into the duodenum where it helps in the digestion of proteins into smaller peptides.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"The following organisms are producers except","images":[],"options":{"A":"Hibiscus","B":"Mushroom","C":"Cactus","D":"Spirogyra"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Producers, also known as autotrophs, are organisms that can produce their own food from the substances available in their surroundings using light (photosynthesis) or chemical energy (chemosynthesis). Hibiscus, Cactus, and Spirogyra are all producers because they can perform photosynthesis. However, mushrooms are not producers. They are fungi, which are heterotrophs, meaning they cannot produce their own food and rely on other organisms for nutrition.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following structures produces the greatest variety of digestive enzymes?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Salivary glands","B":"Pancreas","C":"Stomach","D":"Colon"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The pancreas produces the greatest variety of digestive enzymes. These include amylase, which breaks down carbohydrates; lipase, which breaks down fats; and protease, which breaks down proteins. The salivary glands produce salivary amylase, the stomach produces pepsin, and the colon does not produce digestive enzymes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"The following are abiotic components of an ecosystem except","images":[],"options":{"A":"temperature","B":"oxygen","C":"bacteria","D":"soil"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Bacteria are biotic components of an ecosystem. Biotic components refer to all the living organisms in an ecosystem, including animals, plants, fungi, and microorganisms such as bacteria. Abiotic components, on the other hand, refer to non-living physical and chemical elements in an ecosystem, such as temperature, oxygen, and soil.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"Use the information on capture-recapture method to calculate the total number of organisms in a habitat     First capture = 200   Second capture = 120    Number of organisms with mark in second capture = 40  `  The total number of organisms therefore is","images":[],"options":{"A":"200","B":"360","C":"600","D":"800"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The capture-recapture method is a method used in ecology to estimate an animal's population size. A portion of the population is captured, marked, and released. Later, another portion is captured and the number of marked individuals within the sample is counted. The total population is estimated using the formula: (first capture * second capture) / number of marked recaptures. In this case, (200 * 120) / 40 = 600. Therefore, the total number of organisms in the habitat is estimated to be 600.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT","question":"Ecological investigation in a habitat includes the following procedures except","images":[],"options":{"A":"choosing a habitat","B":"identification of specimen","C":"determining the genetic make-up of specimen","D":"measuring abiotic and biotic factors"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Ecological investigation in a habitat includes choosing a habitat, identification of specimen, and measuring abiotic (non-living) and biotic (living) factors. However, determining the genetic make-up of a specimen is not a standard procedure in ecological investigation. This is more related to the field of genetics and molecular biology, where the genetic material of an organism is studied.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following substances when lost from the body of a mammal will *not* be returned to the ecosystem?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Sweat","B":"Urea","C":"Heat Energy","D":"Carbon dioxide"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Heat energy, once lost from the body of a mammal, is not returned to the ecosystem. This is because heat energy is a form of kinetic energy that is dissipated into the environment and cannot be recycled or reused. On the other hand, substances like sweat, urea, and carbon dioxide can be returned to the ecosystem through various biological processes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"The rate of decomposition of organisms is faster in the tropical rain forest than in other biomes because","images":[],"options":{"A":"of the relatively constant daylight","B":"there are more plants per square feet","C":"of abundance of water","D":"of constant cool temperature"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The rate of decomposition of organisms is faster in the tropical rain forest than in other biomes because of the abundance of water. Water is a key factor in decomposition as it aids in the breakdown of organic matter and promotes the growth and activity of decomposers like bacteria and fungi. The other options do not directly contribute to the rate of decomposition.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"A xerophyte conserves water by possession of the following features except","images":[],"options":{"A":"thick cuticle","B":"sunken stomata","C":"broad leaves","D":"fleshy stems"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A xerophyte is a plant that is adapted to survive in an environment with little liquid water, such as an arid desert or an ice- or snow-covered region in the Alps or the Arctic. They have adaptations that help them conserve water, such as thick cuticles, sunken stomata, and fleshy stems. However, they do not have broad leaves. Broad leaves would increase the surface area for evaporation, which would lead to more water loss. Therefore, the correct answer is 'broad leaves'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The falling off of leaves of deciduous trees is helpful to the plant because it","images":[],"options":{"A":"reduces the rate of transpiration","B":"enables the plant to conveniently  eliminate its excretory products","C":"enables the plants to bear more fruits","D":"ensures that the limited mineral salts get to only growing regions"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Deciduous trees are trees that shed their leaves annually as an adaptation to a cold or dry season. The falling off of leaves reduces the rate of transpiration (water loss) because there are fewer leaves to lose water. This is particularly important in winter when water can be hard to absorb from frozen ground. Therefore, the correct answer is 'reduces the rate of transpiration'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"A sample of wet garden soil of known weight was heated to constant weight. The loss of weight is due to loss of","images":[],"options":{"A":"water","B":"organic matter","C":"water and organic matter","D":"water and inorganic matter"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Water, only contribute to the weight of the garden soil.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : FACTORS THAT AFFECT POPULATION","question":"Assuming that a period of stable population size is followed by a period when natality increases by ten(10)percent and immigration increases by twenty(2)) percent of population size. The population size will","images":[],"options":{"A":"be at equilibrium","B":"increase by forty(40) percent","C":"begin to increase","D":"begin to decrease"},"answer":"C","explanation":"If natality (birth rate) increases by 10 percent and immigration (influx of individuals into a population) increases by 20 percent, the population size will begin to increase. This is because both natality and immigration contribute to an increase in population size. Therefore, if both of these factors increase, the overall population size will also begin to increase.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : TOWARDS BETTER HEALTH","question":"Which of the following methods does not make water fit for drinking?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Addition of chlorine","B":"Boiling","C":"Distillation","D":"Addition of alum"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The addition of alum does not make water fit for drinking. Alum is used in water purification to cause impurities to coagulate and settle at the bottom, but it does not kill bacteria or other microorganisms that may be present in the water. Therefore, while it can help to clarify water, it does not make it safe to drink.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : TOWARDS BETTER HEALTH","question":"Vaccination results in","images":[],"options":{"A":"aiding red bloods cells to carry more oxygen","B":"production of antibodies which destroy toxins of germs","C":"arresting excessive bleeding","D":"production of white blood cells which engulf and digest bacteria"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Vaccination works by stimulating the immune system to produce antibodies, which are proteins that can recognize and neutralize specific pathogens. These antibodies can destroy toxins produced by germs, thereby preventing disease. The other options are not correct because vaccination does not aid red blood cells to carry more oxygen, arrest excessive bleeding, or directly produce white blood cells that engulf and digest bacteria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : RELEVANCE OF BIOLOGY TO AGRICULTURE","question":"Leguminous crops are incorporated into crop rotation in order to","images":[],"options":{"A":"improve aeration of the soil","B":"promote nitrogen fixation","C":"increase the rate of soil formation","D":"improve upon the water holding capacity of the soil."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Leguminous crops are incorporated into crop rotation to promote nitrogen fixation. Nitrogen fixation is a process by which nitrogen in the atmosphere is converted into ammonia (NH3) or related nitrogenous compounds in soil. Leguminous plants have symbiotic bacteria called Rhizobium in their root nodules that help in nitrogen fixation, thus enriching the soil with nitrogen and improving its fertility.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : RELEVANCE OF BIOLOGY TO AGRICULTURE","question":"Which of the following practices improves crop yield in a clayey soil? Addition of","images":[],"options":{"A":"more water and humus","B":"lime and humus","C":"fertilizers","D":"weedicides and fertilizers"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Clayey soil is compact and has poor drainage. Adding lime and humus improves the structure of the clayey soil. Lime increases the pH of the soil, making it less acidic, and humus improves the soil's nutrient content and water holding capacity, thus improving crop yield.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"Which of the following activities promotes forest conservation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Lumbering","B":"Use of firewood for cooking","C":"Afforestation","D":"Production of paper"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Forest conservation involves the upkeep of the natural resources within a forest that are beneficial to both humans and the environment. It's a broad term that includes activities like reforestation, afforestation, and preventing deforestation. Afforestation, which is the process of establishing a forest, or stand of trees, in an area where there was no forest, is a direct action towards forest conservation. Lumbering, use of firewood for cooking, and production of paper are activities that actually lead to deforestation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following statements is not true about continuous variation? It","images":[],"options":{"A":"is usually controlled by several genes","B":"can be influenced by environmental factors","C":"follows a normal distribution curve","D":"is usually controlled by one or two pairs(s) of genes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Continuous variation refers to a range of small differences in a shared trait among individuals. It is usually controlled by several genes (polygenic), can be influenced by environmental factors, and follows a normal distribution curve. The statement that it is usually controlled by one or two pairs of genes is incorrect because this describes discrete variation, not continuous variation. Discrete variation is controlled by a single gene or a small number of genes and results in distinct categories, such as blood type or sex.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>51","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Acquired characters are","images":[],"options":{"A":"received from parents","B":"passed to offspring","C":"caused by the environment","D":"caused by mutation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Acquired characters are traits that an organism develops during its lifetime as a result of environmental influences or other external factors. These traits are not inherited from parents or passed on to offspring. They are caused by the environment, not by mutation. Therefore, the correct answer is 'caused by the environment'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>52","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Differences in characteristics observed between individuals of the same species is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"trait","B":"phenotype","C":"mutation","D":"variation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Differences in characteristics observed between individuals of the same species is known as variation. Traits are specific characteristics, phenotype is the physical expression of an organism's genetic makeup, and mutation is a change in the DNA sequence. Variation, on the other hand, refers to the differences in characteristics among individuals of the same species. Therefore, the correct answer is 'variation'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>53","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"Which of the following statements best describes protein synthesis?","images":[],"options":{"A":"DNA is directly involved in translation","B":"Translocation of the ribosomes exposes a new codon for base pairing with an amino acid","C":"Each tRNA with a particular anticodon always carries a different protein in the process.","D":"One amino acid is always carried by more than one tRNA"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Protein synthesis is a two-step process that includes transcription and translation. During translation, the ribosome moves along the mRNA, which is a process known as translocation. This exposes a new codon for base pairing with an amino acid. Therefore, the statement 'Translocation of the ribosomes exposes a new codon for base pairing with an amino acid' best describes protein synthesis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>54","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"If a person has two alleles of the sickle cell anaemia gene, the person","images":[],"options":{"A":"is a heterozygous carrier of the disease","B":"is immune to the disease and cannot pass on it on to an offspring.","C":"has the disease","D":"is probably of Asian ancestry"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Sickle cell anaemia is a genetic disease that is caused by the presence of two sickle cell genes. If a person has two alleles of the sickle cell anaemia gene, it means that the person has the disease. Therefore, the statement 'has the disease' is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>55","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"What is the probability of a man of blood group AB married to a woman of blood group O producing a child of blood group O?","images":[],"options":{"A":"0%","B":"25%","C":"50%","D":"75%"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The probability is 0. In genetics, blood type gene has two alleles, each allele has genotype A, B or O. The A and B are dominant, and O is recessive. So allele A combined with allele O is type A. Similarly, BO is type B, AA is type A, BB is type B, OO is type O, and AB is type AB.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>56","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"A man with blood group IAIA is married to a woman with blood group IAIO. The blood group of their son is likely to be","images":[],"options":{"A":"A","B":"0","C":"B","D":"AB"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The man with blood group IAIA can only pass on an A allele to his offspring. The woman with blood group IAIO can pass on either an A or O allele. Therefore, their son could either be blood group A (IAIA or IAi) or blood group O (ii), but not B or AB. The most likely blood group is A, because there are two ways to get this (IAIA or IAi), compared to only one way to get blood group O (ii).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>57","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Natural selection is a consequence of","images":[],"options":{"A":"distribution of organisms","B":"adverse conditions","C":"variation in organisms","D":"inbreeding"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Natural selection is a consequence of variation in organisms. This is because natural selection is a process where organisms that are better adapted to their environment tend to survive and produce more offspring. This is based on the variations that exist within a species, where some individuals are more adapted to the environment than others. The individuals with the beneficial traits are more likely to survive and pass on these traits to the next generation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>58","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following components of Larmark's theory of evolution is considered faulty?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Individuals of the same species growing under different environmental conditions differ from each other","B":"Use of certain organs results in development of those parts","C":"Unused organs degenerate","D":"Changes that result in individuals of the same species are transmitted to offspring"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Due to unfavourable and adverse conidition situation of survival of thee fittest come up which leads to natural selection","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>59","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"A vestigial in humans is","images":[],"options":{"A":"earlobe","B":"toe bone","C":"tail bone","D":"spleen"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A vestigial structure is an anatomical feature that no longer seems to have a purpose in the current form of an organism of the given species. The tail bone, or coccyx, in humans is a vestigial structure. It is the remnant of a lost tail, all that remains of the tail that most mammals still use.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2011>60","subject":"Biology","year":"2011","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Adenine pairs with Thymine because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the two occur in the same nucleic acid","B":"one is a strong base and the other a weak base","C":"two purine bases easily pair up","D":"one is purine base and the other a pyrimidine"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In DNA, adenine (A) forms a base pair with thymine (T). This is because adenine is a purine and thymine is a pyrimidine, and their molecular structures allow them to bond together with hydrogen bonds. Purines and pyrimidines are the two types of nitrogenous bases found in nucleic acids. Purines are larger, two-ring compounds, and pyrimidines are smaller, one-ring compounds. This size complementarity allows for a purine to always pair with a pyrimidine, which ensures consistent distance between DNA strands in a double helix and thus its structural stability.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];